<font color="#FF0000">COOK &amp; SW, AND EVERYONE ELSE</font><br>
<tt>Thu Sep 18 20:40:41 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
SW,<br><br>
The trip down to the bottom where the demons reside is no fun. Chet is right on about internalizing it. I did the same thing, so I have been told. I felt a compelling need to visit my demon friends. I did. What I saw was not pretty or comforting. The demons were me. <br><br>
Cook, SW is correct in the value of equilibrium. If you have it, don't mess with it! I did not have much of it at all. Equilibrium is something I seek. I have it sort of tenuously now, subject to periodic up and down cycles if I am triggered. I handle that with the skills I have learned with my mental health professionals, antidepressants, and once in a while with atavan if I slide too far beyond the point of no return.<br><br>
My biggest challenge is learning my triggers. My most obvious one is the Vietnam movie or scene. &quot;Forrest Gump&quot; left me standing in the parking lot of the theater in really bad shape. I checked out for days. Dissociation can last days or weeks or months, depending on the level of trigger. Movies about abused children. I used to trip out just meeting another Vet, but I can control that one now. Loud noises. A friend banged my car door a few days ago in jest simulating striking another vehicle. I went over the edge for a while. Certain songs. The list can go on and on. I pattern my life now to avoid the identified triggers. '96 4th of July left me gonzo. '97 wasn't so bad. 3/4 gonzo on meds. Airplane trips, crowds, being in the middle of a room full of people drives me absolutely nuts. I always stand along a wall near a door where no one is behind me and I can see everything. Same for a restaurant. Nov, Dec, and Jan are my bad months. It was really black for me in Nam then.<br><br>
That's enough! This is a good exercise for me, but I am sure I am starting to be a little boring. <br><br>
I get dinged once on a while from some fellow Vets about going public about all this. I don't advertise it, but I will explain a few things to people if they question some of my behavioral quirks. When I let it out that I informed my employer of all this, it really brought the house down. People are scared stiff of discrimination of individuals with PTSD. Well folks, that is what the ADA is all about. I am still employed.<br><br>
I look at it this way, I got this through no fault of my own, I have identified it, and I am taking agressive steps to bring it under control. I like myself better that way. If people can't respect that, even if they don't really understand very much about PTSD, they are not worth the time of day.<br><br>
Art
